metadata.name: Alice's Creative Journey #14
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, in a world where art was created by algorithms and machines, there lived a brilliant programmer named Alice. Alice was fascinated by generative art, and spent most of her days experimenting with different techniques and algorithms to create unique and intriguing visual designs.

One day, Alice decided to try her hand at using the rough.js library to create a piece of generative art using only rectangles. She began by setting up the canvas and defining a few simple parameters for her design, such as the size and position of the shapes, and the degree of randomness she wanted to introduce into the final piece.

As she began to code, Alice felt a sense of excitement and creativity wash over her. She loved the way the shapes seemed to dance and interweave on the screen as she played with the parameters, creating endless variations and combinations.

Eventually, Alice hit upon a particularly beautiful and harmonious arrangement of rectangles, and she knew she had found the perfect composition for her generative art piece. She saved the design and sat back to admire her work, feeling a sense of pride and accomplishment wash over her.

And so, with the help of the rough.js library and her own creativity and vision, Alice had created a stunning and unique piece of generative art that would be admired by all who saw it.

In live mode click "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
Alice's Creative Journey by __Reiji_c

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #99
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: The Esoteric Form #25
metadata.description:
The circle is an amazing strange geometrical form, it is by far the simplest geometric shape that exists, you might disagree with that, but actually, there are hundreds of pages long of mathematical proof of why it is, it's called "The PoincarÃ© conjecture" this is one of the most difficult problems that stayed unsolved 20th century to prove that a circle is the simplest shape until it was demonstrated in 2003. When you see a drawing circle, it's a circle in two dimensions, right? What would it look like if it was in three dimensions, it's a sphere; same shape but more dimensions, but it's still the simplest kind of shape that exists in three dimensions. No matter how many dimensions you add, according to the PoincarÃ© conjecture, it will always be the simplest shape. Even though it seems straightforward, there are extremely profoundÂ difficult problems within it.

The astonishing thing about circlesÂ is what we can do with them, particularly by using the majestic number Ï€Â and connecting straight and curved lines using topological or geometrical functions. "The esoteric form" project is an example of how a circle can take on countless shapes and unusual, vibrant forms while also being simple and complex at the same time.

metadata.name: The Cosmos #1
metadata.description:
In astronomy, kosmos refers to the entire physical cosmos as a cohesive whole (from the Greek kosmos, which means "order," "harmony," and "the world"). Humanity's increasing comprehension of all the things and occurrences in the universe.

To understand how the world works, we must first investigate the fundamental components of our existence - time, space, energy and matter - and how they operate under the extraordinary physical conditions that define the infant and evolving Universe.

Scientists, particularly astrophysicists, are directly tackling fundamental issues concerning the nature of complicated astrophysical phenomena such as black holes, neutron stars, dark energy, and gravitational waves. Their ultimate, overarching objective is to learn more about the genesis and purpose of existence of the cosmos by employing a fleet of space-based missions operating across the whole electromagnetic spectrum.

The universe is largely made up of both helium and hydrogen. Indeed, these two elements account for 98% of all observable substance in the cosmos. Nonetheless, our planet and everything in itâ€”even life itselfâ€”are only imaginable due to the presence of heavier elements including iron, silicon, oxygen, nitrogen, carbon, and a plethora of others.

However, all of this comprehension leaded through the quest of the meaning of the cosmos, which originated with the emergence of life, will vanish with its conclusion. That leaves us only one realization: we are responsible with discovering our own meaning during our brief stint in the sun.

Press [s] to save captured image to png (6600px x 6600px)

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used,Â the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.Â

metadata.name: Timeless Machine #28
metadata.description:
Does time traveling on Earth or a time machine in real life?

Future travel is a possibility! We frequently carry it out! I'm moving forward at the speed of one second per second while I type this. No machine is necessary. But you just have to go faster if you want to get to the future faster.

Our project presents the most revolutionized time machine in the advanced parallel universe. The quantum time machine creation was based on the invention of the last piece of the puzzle ever searched for; "Fastium" the darkest and the strongest matter ever. The time machine has twelve stratum; each one is a complex mechanical power field based on pinions created by liquefying the Fastium, whose melting point is the Planck temperature, then crystallizes the Fastium by putting it into the absolute zero states; by passing through this complex process, the pinions made of Fastium have gained the capacity to rotate surpassing the speed of light. The simultaneous inversed rotation of each stratum of pinions distorts space-time, and magically each pinion causes its distortion procreating it in twelve dimensions. The distortion of space-time in all twelve dimensions at once is a rare instance that can travel you through an unknown future that may be the end of all existence; you have to be cautious. Each number of dimensions distorted spawns a destination in a futuristic time that you can jump to.

If you encounter a specific "Time Machine" that you've liked, you can pause the switching effects by clicking "the left mouse button"

Created using vanilla javascript

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #42
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.
